<!--
Percent Page Scrolled Overview:
This code uses the jQuery scroll method to bind an event handler to the scroll javascript event.
After a scroll has occurred, the position on the page is recorded. The maximum scroll depth is 
recorded in the variable 'maxScroll'.
Using the jQuery unload method, when a user exits the current page, a variable 'intervalLevel' is populated
based on the 'interval' variable defined. Through the resulting calculations, the scroll depth will be set to 
a friendly interval, such as 0, 25, 50, 75, or 100, assuming the use of 25 as the interval.
After this calculation is performed, the GTM dataLayer will be updated with the variable 'percent scrolled', 
and the event of 'record_scroll' will be pushed to the data layer.

GTM Setup:
The below code should be added as a custom HTML tag in GTM.
It should be set to fire at the custom event of 'gtm.dom', to minimize issues of jQuery not loading yet.
You will also need to create a User-Defined Variable named 'percent scrolled'.
The type of this variable is Data Layer Variable, and the Data Layer Variable Name 
to use is also percent scrolled.
Now you are ready to add the tag you want to send to your platform, i.e. Google Analytics.
Create a new tag, and to populate the intervalLevel, you should insert the { {percent_scrolled} } 
variable into the desired field.
For the trigger of the rule, you should use a custom event, with the event name of 'record_scroll'.
-->

<script type='text/javascript'>
function getScrollPosition() {
  scrollObject = {
    x: window.pageXOffset,
    y: window.pageYOffset
  }
  return scrollObject.y;
}

if (typeof jQuery !== 'undefined') {
  var pageHeight = jQuery(document).height();
  var viewportHeight = jQuery(window).height();
  var initialPercent = viewportHeight / pageHeight;
  if (initialPercent > 1) {
    initialPercent = 100;
  } else {
    initialPercent = Math.round(initialPercent * 100);
  }
  var maxScroll = initialPercent;
  
  jQuery(window).scroll(function() {
    var s = getScrollPosition(),
      d = jQuery(document).height(),
      c = jQuery(window).height();
    scrollPercent = (s / (d - c)) * 100;
    if (scrollPercent > maxScroll) {
      maxScroll = scrollPercent;
    }
  });

  jQuery(window).on('beforeunload', function(e) {
    var interval = 25; //set the interval here
    var intervalLevel = Math.floor(maxScroll / interval) * interval;
    if (intervalLevel > 100) {
      intervalLevel = 100;
    }
    dataLayer.push({
      'percent_scrolled': intervalLevel,
      'event': 'record_scroll'
    });
  });
}
</script>

    var name = cookieName + "=";

      var c = ca[i];
      while (c.charAt(0) == ' ') c = c.substring(1);
      if (c.indexOf(name) == 0) {
        cookieValue = c.substring(name.length, c.length);

      }
    }
    return cookieValue;
  }
  _sdi.removeCookie = function(cookieName) {

<!--
Percent Page Scrolled Overview:
This code uses the jQuery scroll method to bind an event handler to the scroll javascript event.
After a scroll has occurred, the position on the page is recorded. The maximum scroll depth is 
recorded in the variable 'maxScroll'.
Using the jQuery unload method, when a user exits the current page, a variable 'intervalLevel' is populated
based on the 'interval' variable defined. Through the resulting calculations, the scroll depth will be set to 
a friendly interval, such as 0, 25, 50, 75, or 100, assuming the use of 25 as the interval.
After this calculation is performed, the GTM dataLayer will be updated with the variable 'percent scrolled', 
and the event of 'record_scroll' will be pushed to the data layer.

GTM Setup:
The below code should be added as a custom HTML tag in GTM.
It should be set to fire at the custom event of 'gtm.dom', to minimize issues of jQuery not loading yet.
You will also need to create a User-Defined Variable named 'percent scrolled'.
The type of this variable is Data Layer Variable, and the Data Layer Variable Name 
to use is also percent scrolled.
Now you are ready to add the tag you want to send to your platform, i.e. Google Analytics.
Create a new tag, and to populate the intervalLevel, you should insert the { {percent_scrolled} } 
variable into the desired field.
For the trigger of the rule, you should use a custom event, with the event name of 'record_scroll'.
-->

<script type='text/javascript'>
function getScrollPosition() {
  scrollObject = {
    x: window.pageXOffset,
    y: window.pageYOffset
  }
  return scrollObject.y;
}

if (typeof jQuery !== 'undefined') {
  var pageHeight = jQuery(document).height();
  var viewportHeight = jQuery(window).height();
  var initialPercent = viewportHeight / pageHeight;
  if (initialPercent > 1) {
    initialPercent = 100;
  } else {
    initialPercent = Math.round(initialPercent * 100);
  }
  var maxScroll = initialPercent;
  
  jQuery(window).scroll(function() {
    var s = getScrollPosition(),
      d = jQuery(document).height(),
      c = jQuery(window).height();
    scrollPercent = (s / (d - c)) * 100;
    if (scrollPercent > maxScroll) {
      maxScroll = scrollPercent;
    }
  });

  jQuery(window).on('beforeunload', function(e) {
    var interval = 25; //set the interval here
    var intervalLevel = Math.floor(maxScroll / interval) * interval;
    if (intervalLevel > 100) {
      intervalLevel = 100;
    }
    dataLayer.push({
      'percent_scrolled': intervalLevel,
      'event': 'record_scroll'
    });
  });
}
</script>
